    <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
         KEY PROBLEMS SUMMARY
    ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

    <mxCell id="problems" value="&lt;b&gt;❌  FIVE KEY PROBLEMS WITH THE CURRENT PROCESS&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;1.  Scheduling is carbon-blind — jobs run whenever a node is free, not when the electricity is clean&lt;br/&gt;2.  No job classification — delay-tolerant and time-critical jobs are treated identically by the scheduler&lt;br/&gt;3.  Missed opportunity — carbon intensity varies by up to 2× within a single day on the TVA grid (76–500 gCO₂/kWh)&lt;br/&gt;4.  No measurement — the carbon cost of each job is unknown, making any targeted reduction impossible&lt;br/&gt;5.  CSRD non-compliance — without hourly Scope 2 data, organisations cannot meet EU CSRD disclosure requirements"
      style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fillColor=#ffcccc;strokeColor=#cc0000;align=left;spacingLeft=14;spacingRight=12;spacingTop=8;fontSize=12;fontStyle=1;verticalAlign=top;"
      vertex="1" parent="1">
